    <main id="main">
      <section id="intro" class="section visible">
        <article class="panel theory-panel">
          <div class="section-label">SECTION 01</div>
          <h2>Introduction to C Programming</h2>
          <p class="topic-summary">C is a procedural, compiled language created for systems programming and low-level control. Learning C gives you direct understanding of memory, execution flow, and performance behavior.</p>

          <h3 class="theory-subheading">1.1 Program Structure</h3>
          <ul class="theory-list">
            <li>Preprocessor directives (for example, <code>#include</code>) are handled before compilation.</li>
            <li><code>main()</code> is the entry point of every C program.</li>
            <li>Statements end with semicolons and blocks are scoped with braces.</li>
          </ul>
          <pre><code>#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;

int main(void) {
    printf("Hello, C world!\n");
    return 0;
}</code></pre>

          <h3 class="theory-subheading">1.2 Build Pipeline</h3>
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Stage</th>
                <th>What Happens</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td>Preprocessing</td>
                <td>Expands macros and includes header files.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Compilation</td>
                <td>Converts C source to assembly code.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Assembly</td>
                <td>Converts assembly to object machine code.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Linking</td>
                <td>Combines object code and libraries into executable.</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>

          <h3 class="theory-subheading">1.3 Standards and Use Cases</h3>
          <ul class="theory-list">
            <li>Major language standards: C89/C90, C99, C11, C17, and C23.</li>
            <li>Used in kernels, embedded firmware, device drivers, compilers, and networking stacks.</li>
            <li>In interviews, C is used to evaluate memory awareness and problem-solving fundamentals.</li>
          </ul>

          <p class="theory-note"><strong>Important:</strong> C gives high control and high responsibility. Invalid memory access, uninitialized variables, and buffer overflow can cause undefined behavior.</p>

          <div class="mark-row">
            <label><input type="checkbox" data-topic="intro"> Mark topic as completed</label>
            <button class="btn next-btn" data-next="datatypes" type="button">Next Topic</button>
          </div>
        </article>
        <article class="panel examples-panel">
          <h3>Solved Examples (10)</h3>
          <div id="examples-intro" class="examples-list"></div>
        </article>
      </section>

      <section id="datatypes" class="section">
        <article class="panel theory-panel">
          <div class="section-label">SECTION 02</div>
          <h2>Data Types in C</h2>
          <p class="topic-summary">C is statically typed, so every variable must be declared with a type before usage. Type selection affects memory size, precision, and valid operations.</p>

          <h3 class="theory-subheading">2.1 Primitive Types and Formats</h3>
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Type</th>
                <th>Typical Size</th>
                <th>Format Specifier</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td><code>char</code></td>
                <td>1 byte</td>
                <td><code>%c</code></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><code>int</code></td>
                <td>4 bytes</td>
                <td><code>%d</code></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><code>float</code></td>
                <td>4 bytes</td>
                <td><code>%f</code></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><code>double</code></td>
                <td>8 bytes</td>
                <td><code>%lf</code></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><code>long long</code></td>
                <td>8 bytes</td>
                <td><code>%lld</code></td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>

          <h3 class="theory-subheading">2.2 Modifiers, Qualifiers, and Casting</h3>
          <pre><code>#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;

int main(void) {
    unsigned int u = 42u;
    const int maxUsers = 100;
    int a = 7, b = 2;

    printf("u = %u\n", u);
    printf("maxUsers = %d\n", maxUsers);
    printf("Integer division = %d\n", a / b);
    printf("Float division = %.2f\n", (float)a / b);
    return 0;
}</code></pre>

          <h3 class="theory-subheading">2.3 Signed vs Unsigned and Overflow</h3>
          <ul class="theory-list">
            <li><code>unsigned</code> types store only non-negative values.</li>
            <li>Signed overflow is undefined behavior, while unsigned overflow wraps modulo 2<sup>N</sup>.</li>
            <li>Always use <code>sizeof(type)</code> instead of assuming sizes across systems.</li>
          </ul>

          <p class="theory-note"><strong>Interview Tip:</strong> Explain both memory size and range implications when choosing a type. Correct format specifiers are as important as type declarations.</p>

          <div class="mark-row">
            <label><input type="checkbox" data-topic="datatypes"> Mark topic as completed</label>
            <button class="btn next-btn" data-next="control" type="button">Next Topic</button>
          </div>
        </article>
        <article class="panel examples-panel">
          <h3>Solved Examples (10)</h3>
          <div id="examples-datatypes" class="examples-list"></div>
        </article>
      </section>

      <section id="control" class="section">
        <article class="panel theory-panel">
          <div class="section-label">SECTION 03</div>
          <h2>Control Flow</h2>
          <p class="topic-summary">Control flow determines program path based on conditions and decisions. In C, the main tools are conditional branches, switch dispatch, and jump statements.</p>

          <h3 class="theory-subheading">3.1 if / else if / else</h3>
          <pre><code>#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;

int main(void) {
    int score;
    scanf("%d", &score);

    if (score >= 90) {
        printf("Grade A\n");
    } else if (score >= 75) {
        printf("Grade B\n");
    } else {
        printf("Grade C or below\n");
    }
    return 0;
}</code></pre>

          <h3 class="theory-subheading">3.2 switch-case</h3>
          <pre><code>#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;

int main(void) {
    int day;
    scanf("%d", &day);

    switch (day) {
        case 1: printf("Monday\n"); break;
        case 2: printf("Tuesday\n"); break;
        case 3: printf("Wednesday\n"); break;
        default: printf("Invalid day\n");
    }
    return 0;
}</code></pre>

          <h3 class="theory-subheading">3.3 Ternary and Jump Statements</h3>
          <pre><code>#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;

int main(void) {
    int a = 10, b = 20;
    int max = (a > b) ? a : b;

    for (int i = 0; i &lt; 10; i++) {
        if (i == 5) break;
        if (i % 2 == 0) continue;
        printf("%d ", i);
    }

    printf("\nMax = %d\n", max);
    return 0;
}</code></pre>
          <ul class="theory-list">
            <li><code>break</code> exits current loop/switch.</li>
            <li><code>continue</code> skips current iteration and jumps to next.</li>
            <li><code>return</code> exits a function with optional value.</li>
            <li><code>goto</code> exists in C but should be used very carefully.</li>
          </ul>

          <p class="theory-note"><strong>Common Bug:</strong> Missing <code>break</code> in <code>switch</code> causes fall-through into the next case.</p>

          <div class="mark-row">
            <label><input type="checkbox" data-topic="control"> Mark topic as completed</label>
            <button class="btn next-btn" data-next="loops" type="button">Next Topic</button>
          </div>
        </article>
        <article class="panel examples-panel">
          <h3>Solved Examples (10)</h3>
          <div id="examples-control" class="examples-list"></div>
        </article>
      </section>

      <section id="loops" class="section">
        <article class="panel theory-panel">
          <div class="section-label">SECTION 04</div>
          <h2>Loops</h2>
          <p class="topic-summary">Loops repeat blocks of code while a condition is true. C has three loop types: <code>for</code>, <code>while</code>, and <code>do-while</code>.</p>

          <h3 class="theory-subheading">4.1 for Loop (Known Iteration Count)</h3>
          <pre><code>#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;

int main(void) {
    for (int i = 1; i &lt;= 5; i++) {
        printf("%d ", i);
    }
    return 0;
}</code></pre>

          <h3 class="theory-subheading">4.2 while Loop (Condition Driven)</h3>
          <pre><code>#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;

int main(void) {
    int n = 5;
    while (n > 0) {
        printf("%d ", n);
        n--;
    }
    return 0;
}</code></pre>

          <h3 class="theory-subheading">4.3 do-while Loop (Runs At Least Once)</h3>
          <pre><code>#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;

int main(void) {
    int x;
    do {
        scanf("%d", &x);
    } while (x &lt;= 0);

    printf("Valid input: %d\n", x);
    return 0;
}</code></pre>

          <h3 class="theory-subheading">4.4 Nested Loops and Loop Controls</h3>
          <pre><code>#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;

int main(void) {
    for (int row = 1; row &lt;= 3; row++) {
        for (int col = 1; col &lt;= row; col++) {
            printf("*");
        }
        printf("\n");
    }
    return 0;
}</code></pre>
          <ul class="theory-list">
            <li>Use <code>break</code> to terminate loops early when condition met.</li>
            <li>Use <code>continue</code> to skip invalid or unnecessary iterations.</li>
            <li>Avoid infinite loops unless intentionally building long-running services.</li>
          </ul>

          <p class="theory-note"><strong>Interview Tip:</strong> Be ready to explain time complexity of nested loops. For example, two nested loops often mean O(n<sup>2</sup>) complexity.</p>

          <div class="mark-row">
            <label><input type="checkbox" data-topic="loops"> Mark topic as completed</label>
            <button class="btn next-btn" data-next="arrays" type="button">Next Topic</button>
          </div>
        </article>
        <article class="panel examples-panel">
          <h3>Solved Examples (10)</h3>
          <div id="examples-loops" class="examples-list"></div>
        </article>
      </section>

      <section id="arrays" class="section">
        <article class="panel theory-panel">
          <div class="section-label">SECTION 05</div>
          <h2>Arrays</h2>
          <p class="topic-summary">An array is a contiguous block of memory storing same-type elements. Arrays are indexed from 0 and are heavily used in searching, sorting, and matrix problems.</p>

          <h3 class="theory-subheading">5.1 Declaration, Initialization, Traversal</h3>
          <pre><code>#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;

int main(void) {
    int arr[5] = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};
    for (int i = 0; i &lt; 5; i++) {
        printf("arr[%d] = %d\n", i, arr[i]);
    }
    return 0;
}</code></pre>

          <h3 class="theory-subheading">5.2 Passing Arrays to Functions</h3>
          <pre><code>#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;

void printArray(int arr[], int n) {
    for (int i = 0; i &lt; n; i++) {
        printf("%d ", arr[i]);
    }
    printf("\n");
}

int main(void) {
    int values[] = {2, 4, 6, 8};
    printArray(values, 4);
    return 0;
}</code></pre>

          <h3 class="theory-subheading">5.3 2D Arrays (Matrix Form)</h3>
          <pre><code>#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;

int main(void) {
    int matrix[2][3] = {{1, 2, 3}, {4, 5, 6}};

    for (int i = 0; i &lt; 2; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j &lt; 3; j++) {
            printf("%d ", matrix[i][j]);
        }
        printf("\n");
    }
    return 0;
}</code></pre>

          <ul class="theory-list">
            <li>C does not perform bounds checking on array indices.</li>
            <li>Passing an array to a function decays it into a pointer to first element.</li>
            <li>Always track array length separately to avoid out-of-bounds access.</li>
          </ul>

          <p class="theory-note"><strong>Common Error:</strong> Accessing <code>arr[n]</code> in an array of size <code>n</code> is out-of-bounds and causes undefined behavior.</p>

          <div class="mark-row">
            <label><input type="checkbox" data-topic="arrays"> Mark topic as completed</label>
            <button class="btn next-btn" data-next="strings" type="button">Next Topic</button>
          </div>
        </article>
        <article class="panel examples-panel">
          <h3>Solved Examples (10)</h3>
          <div id="examples-arrays" class="examples-list"></div>
        </article>
      </section>

      <section id="strings" class="section">
        <article class="panel theory-panel">
          <div class="section-label">SECTION 06</div>
          <h2>Strings in C</h2>
          <p class="topic-summary">C has no built-in string type; a string is a null-terminated character array. Reliable string handling requires careful boundary checks and safe input methods.</p>

          <h3 class="theory-subheading">6.1 String Representation</h3>
          <pre><code>#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;

int main(void) {
    char s1[] = "Hello";      // Mutable array copy
    const char *s2 = "World"; // String literal pointer

    printf("%s %s\n", s1, s2);
    return 0;
}</code></pre>

          <h3 class="theory-subheading">6.2 Safe Input and Output</h3>
          <pre><code>#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;
#include &lt;string.h&gt;

int main(void) {
    char line[100];
    fgets(line, sizeof(line), stdin);
    line[strcspn(line, "\n")] = '\0';

    printf("You typed: %s\n", line);
    return 0;
}</code></pre>

          <h3 class="theory-subheading">6.3 Common Functions in &lt;string.h&gt;</h3>
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Function</th>
                <th>Purpose</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td><code>strlen(s)</code></td>
                <td>Returns length excluding null terminator.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><code>strcpy(dest, src)</code></td>
                <td>Copies source string to destination.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><code>strcat(dest, src)</code></td>
                <td>Appends source to destination string.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><code>strcmp(a, b)</code></td>
                <td>Compares two strings lexicographically.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><code>strstr(s, sub)</code></td>
                <td>Finds first occurrence of substring.</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>

          <ul class="theory-list">
            <li>A string literal should be treated as read-only memory.</li>
            <li>Always ensure destination buffer has enough capacity before copying/concatenating.</li>
            <li>Prefer bounded APIs where available to reduce overflow risk.</li>
          </ul>

          <p class="theory-note"><strong>Security Note:</strong> Unchecked string writes are a major source of vulnerabilities in C codebases.</p>

          <div class="mark-row">
            <label><input type="checkbox" data-topic="strings"> Mark topic as completed</label>
            <button class="btn next-btn" data-next="pointers" type="button">Next Topic</button>
          </div>
        </article>
        <article class="panel examples-panel">
          <h3>Solved Examples (10)</h3>
          <div id="examples-strings" class="examples-list"></div>
        </article>
      </section>

      <section id="pointers" class="section">
        <article class="panel theory-panel">
          <div class="section-label">SECTION 07</div>
          <h2>Pointers</h2>
          <p class="topic-summary">Pointers store addresses and make direct memory manipulation possible. They are essential in arrays, dynamic memory, linked lists, and function-based data updates.</p>

          <h3 class="theory-subheading">7.1 Address and Dereference</h3>
          <pre><code>#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;

int main(void) {
    int x = 42;
    int *p = &x;

    printf("Address of x: %p\n", (void *)&x);
    printf("Value via p: %d\n", *p);
    return 0;
}</code></pre>

          <h3 class="theory-subheading">7.2 Pointer Arithmetic</h3>
          <pre><code>#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;

int main(void) {
    int arr[] = {10, 20, 30};
    int *ptr = arr;

    printf("%d\n", *ptr);       // arr[0]
    printf("%d\n", *(ptr + 1)); // arr[1]
    printf("%d\n", *(ptr + 2)); // arr[2]
    return 0;
}</code></pre>

          <h3 class="theory-subheading">7.3 Pointers with Functions (Call by Reference)</h3>
          <pre><code>#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;

void swap(int *a, int *b) {
    int t = *a;
    *a = *b;
    *b = t;
}

int main(void) {
    int x = 5, y = 9;
    swap(&x, &y);
    printf("x=%d y=%d\n", x, y);
    return 0;
}</code></pre>

          <h3 class="theory-subheading">7.4 Pointer Safety and Dynamic Memory</h3>
          <ul class="theory-list">
            <li><strong>Null pointer:</strong> points to no valid object, check before dereference.</li>
            <li><strong>Wild pointer:</strong> uninitialized pointer with garbage address.</li>
            <li><strong>Dangling pointer:</strong> points to freed or out-of-scope memory.</li>
          </ul>
          <pre><code>#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;
#include &lt;stdlib.h&gt;

int main(void) {
    int *arr = (int *)malloc(3 * sizeof(int));
    if (arr == NULL) return 0;

    arr[0] = 1; arr[1] = 2; arr[2] = 3;
    printf("%d %d %d\n", arr[0], arr[1], arr[2]);

    free(arr);
    arr = NULL;
    return 0;
}</code></pre>

          <p class="theory-note"><strong>Interview Tip:</strong> If asked about pointers, always mention lifetime, ownership, and safety checks along with syntax.</p>

          <div class="mark-row">
            <label><input type="checkbox" data-topic="pointers"> Mark topic as completed</label>
            <button class="btn next-btn" data-next="mem-section" type="button">Try Memory Simulator</button>
          </div>
        </article>
        <article class="panel examples-panel">
          <h3>Solved Examples (10)</h3>
          <div id="examples-pointers" class="examples-list"></div>
        </article>
      </section>

